    <!-- Q1 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 01</span>
        <div class="qa-question">How many log sources are available in QRadar?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>Navigate to <strong>Admin → Data Sources → Log Sources</strong> in the QRadar console. The Log Sources
            table lists every configured source ingesting data into QRadar. A quick count of the entries reveals the
            total.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/LogSources.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption">Figure 1: Admin panel → Log Sources table showing all 15 sources</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span class="qa-answer-value">15</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q2 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 02</span>
        <div class="qa-question">What is the IDS software used to monitor the network?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>In the same Log Sources view, filtering by source type or scanning the log source names reveals an IDS
            entry. The log source name clearly identifies the IDS product in use — it appears as a dedicated entry
            alongside the Windows and Zeek sources.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/IDS.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption">Log Sources — IDS entry highlighted</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span class="qa-answer-value">Suricata</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q3 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 03</span>
        <div class="qa-question">What is the domain name used in the network?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>Search for <strong>Event ID 4720</strong> (User Account Created) to find any newly created accounts. This
            surfaces a single event — a new account named <code>rambo</code> was created during the attack window.</p>
          <p>Taking that username and pivoting to <strong>Event ID 4624</strong> (Successful Logon) filtered by
            <code>username = rambo</code>, the logon event payload includes the full domain name in the account details
            field.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/Domain.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption">4720 event → new user "rambo" | 4624 event → domain field showing
            hackdefend.local</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span
          class="qa-answer-value">hackdefend.local</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q4 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 04</span>
        <div class="qa-question">Multiple IPs communicated with the malicious server. One ends with "20" — provide the
          full IP.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>From the previous question we know the backdoor account <code>rambo</code> was created by an insider host.
            Reviewing the 4720 event payload reveals the <strong>source IP address</strong> that initiated the account
            creation request — the host that the attacker controlled or pivoted through internally.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/ip.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption"> 4720 event payload — source IP 192.168.20.20</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span
          class="qa-answer-value">192.168.20.20</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q5 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 05</span>
        <div class="qa-question">What is the SID of the most frequent alert rule in the dataset?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>In the QRadar Log Activity view, group events by <strong>Rule SID</strong>. This aggregates all Suricata
            IDS alerts by their Snort rule identifier. Sort the grouped results by <strong>Magnitude</strong>
            (descending) to surface the most triggered rule.</p>
          <p>Drilling into the top result and examining the raw event payload, the SID field is visible. Notably, the
            source IP <code>192.168.20.20</code> appears in these events — further confirming it as part of the
            attacker's infrastructure.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/SID3.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption"> Grouped by Rule SID → top result → raw event showing SID 2027865 and src IP
            192.168.20.20</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span class="qa-answer-value">2027865</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q6 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 06</span>
        <div class="qa-question">What is the attacker's external IP address?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>Using <code>192.168.20.20</code> as the pivot point, filter Log Activity grouped by <strong>source IP and
              destination IP</strong>. A large number of IPs appear, but one stands out with two suspicious
            characteristics:</p>
          <ul class="report-list">
            <li><strong>Destination port 448</strong> — not a standard service port, strongly suggesting a custom C2
              listener</li>
            <li><strong>Very high Zeek connection count</strong> — indicating sustained, repeated communication
              consistent with C2 beaconing</li>
          </ul>
          <p>This combination unambiguously identifies the external attacker's IP.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/192ip.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption"> Grouped flows — 192.20.80.25 on port 448 with high Zeek conn count</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span
          class="qa-answer-value">192.20.80.25</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q7 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 07</span>
        <div class="qa-question">The attacker was searching for data belonging to one of the company's projects. What is
          the project name?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>Search the full log payload using a keyword filter: <code>payload contains "project"</code>. This returns
            only four matching log entries. Examining each event reveals the specific project name referenced in the
            attacker's file access or command activity — visible directly in the raw payload field.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/project.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption"> Keyword search "project" → 4 results → payload detail showing "project48"
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span class="qa-answer-value">project48</span>
      </div>
    </div>

