        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/InfectedIP.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption"> Same "project48" log — source IP field showing 192.168.10.15</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span
          class="qa-answer-value">192.168.10.15</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q9 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 09</span>
        <div class="qa-question">What is the username of the infected employee on 192.168.10.15?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>Remaining on the same log event from the previous two questions, the username field in the event payload
            reveals the account associated with that machine. This is the legitimate employee account the attacker was
            operating under after achieving initial access.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/Username.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption"> Same log event — username field showing "nour"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span class="qa-answer-value">nour</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Q10 -->
    <div class="qa-block">
      <div class="qa-header">
        <span class="qa-num">Q 10</span>
        <div class="qa-question">Hackers dislike logging. What logging mechanism was the attacker checking for?</div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-body">
        <div class="qa-solution">
          <p>Filter logs by <code>username = nour</code> and <code>log source = HD-FIN-03</code> (the machine at
            192.168.10.15). The results show a significant volume of PowerShell-related events. Examining the command
            lines reveals the attacker was querying the registry key
            <code>HKLM\Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\PowerShell\ScriptBlockLogging</code> to check whether
            PowerShell script block logging was enabled before proceeding.
          </p>
          <p>This is a standard attacker tradecraft step — confirming the logging landscape before executing malicious
            scripts to avoid leaving detailed evidence.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="report-img-block">
          <img src="images/Qradar/PowerShell.png" alt="   " />
          <p class="img-caption">Filtered by nour + HD-FIN-03 → PowerShell events → registry query for
            ScriptBlockLogging</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="qa-answer"><span class="qa-answer-label">ANSWER</span><span class="qa-answer-value">PowerShell</span>
